16 WHEREAS, the prolonged withdrawal and recovery period can have a profound impact on
17 both physical and mental health, with 81 percent of adults and 56 percent of children
18 experiencing TSWS reporting anxiety or depression and 47 percent of adults and 11 percent
19 of children reporting suicidal ideation; and
20 WHEREAS, the prevalence of topical steroid addiction remains unknown due to a scarcity
21 of published research; and
22 WHEREAS, limited research on TSWS hinders the development of diagnostic criteria; the
23 understanding of its causes, effects, and mechanisms; the establishment of appropriate
24 treatment protocols; and the education of both healthcare providers and patients on TSWS
25 and steroid stewardship; and
26 WHEREAS, a lack of awareness and education about TSWS among both patients and
27 providers can lead to misunderstandings, causing patients to question their providers' medical
28 oversight and leading providers to suspect medication non-compliance or, in some cases,
29 parental neglect; and
30 WHEREAS, all parties would benefit greatly from increased awareness and prevention
31 education on the signs of topical steroid dependence and the risks associated with TSWS.
32 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
33 the members of this body recognize February 3, 2025, as Topical Steroid Withdrawal
34 Syndrome Awareness Day at the state capitol.
